es/jones-sarah-garland-boyd-1866-1905/">Sarah Garland Boyd Jones (1866–1905)</a> in &#8220;How one family owned and ran the largest Black-owned farm in Albemarle County — for generations&#8221;</div></div><footer class=""> <em><a href="/ev-in-the-media/">More in the Media</a></em></footer></section><section class="tile corner histnearu"><header><h2 class="label">History Near You</h2></header> <a href="/map/"> <img src='data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAAEAAAABAQMAAAAl21bKAAAAA1BMVEVHcEyC+tLSAAAAAXRSTlMAQObYZgAAAApJREFUeAFjYAAAAAIAAXN1ARgAAAAASUVORK5CYII=' alt='Find Local History'></a><footer class="bottom-corner"> <em><a href="/map/">Explore Local History</a></em></footer></section> <!--<section class="tile corner"><header><h2 class="label">Podcast Episode</h2></header><div class="podphoto"></div><div class="pod-brief"></div><footer class="bottom-corner"> <em><a href="/podcast/">More from the Podcast</a></em></footer></section>--><section class="tile"><header><h2>On This Day</h2> <em>In Virginia History</em></header><div class="inva"><div class="year">in <time>1726</time></div>Having returned from England to Virginia for the final time, William Byrd II resumes attendance at the governor's Council. <em><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/byrd-william-1674-1744/">Learn More</a></em></div><div class="inva"><div class="year">in <time>1905</time></div>Fitzhugh Lee dies in Washington, D.C. He is buried in Hollywood Cemetery, Richmond. <em><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/lee-fitzhugh-1835-1905/">Learn More</a></em></div><footer> <!--                    <em><a href="">More Entries</a></em>--></footer></section><section class="tile corner a2z"><header><h2 class="label">History A-Z</h2></header> <article id="post-129066" class="entry-brief post-129066 entries type-entries status-publish has-post-thumbnail hentry category-african-american-history category-colonial-history-ca-1560-1763 category-indians category-religion category-slav